          <!-- 
The beginning of the extant part is badly damaged. I transcribe Cunningham's eye copy except that I read yo instead of his ya (and Fleet's tentative la), and gaM with Fleet instead of his gala. (Note that v8 in l6 ends with an anusvāra, not a halanta M, so maybe we have something else here too?) Thaplyal reads r (printed as र्, so perhaps he saw a superscript r here?), followed by dots, then a tentative kṣa and la, and a "clear" gaM. 
-->
          <!-- 
The punctuation character is a double vertical. 
-->
          <!-- 
With Fleet, I assume that verse punctuation was consistently a single daṇḍa at half-verses and a double one at verse ends (though there is no single punctuation at the end of l4 - but this could have been omitted because of the line end). The bit before the double daṇḍa in l1 does not look like the end of a śārdūlavikrīḍita. However, with 72 lost characters, a śārdūlavikrīḍita would be a perfect fit for the lost section. But assuming a prose invocation at the beginning, the verse could be a little shorter. If it's śārdūla, then my conjecture yogam cannot stand; we'd need a long vowel for the kṣ and a short one for the y. 
-->
          <!-- 
At the beginning of l2 we probably have 16 + 2*19 + 15 + 1 syllables lost, which gives 72 (as estimated by Fleet) if we add 2 punctuation characters. At the beginning of l3, we have 15 + 2*19 + 16 characters, which gives 71 with 2 punctuation marks. In l4 we have 3*19 + 12, which is 70 with a punctuation mark. In l5: 2*12 + 2*19 + 4 (+2) = 68. L6: 4 + 3*19 + 5 (+2) = 68. L7: 7 + 2*19 + 18 (+1) = 64. L8: 11 + 2*19 + 14 (+2) = 65. L9: 2*21 + 19 + 5 = 66. L10: 5 + 3*19 + 5 (+2) = 71 
-->
